Read the first like of this article. Here I will help you: (北号作戦, Hoku-gō sakusen, "North"). It says "Hoku-gō sakusen", not "Kita-gō sakusen". It doesn't matter if westerners call it "Operation Banana Hammock", it's still referred to by all Japanese sources as "Operation Hoku". And seeing as this is a Japanese operation with a Japanese name, that's what it ought to use. This has been discussed in the talk section.

BUZZLIGHTYEAR99 moved page [[Talk:Operation Kita]] to [[Talk:Operation Hoku]] over redirect: "Kita" is a mistranslation of the Japanese character for "North" ("北") by foreigners. The operation is named "Hoku" in all Japanese sources, as it uses an alternate pronunciation of the character. "Kita" is erroneously used only in western sources.
